File-Format: Application/pdf
File-Function: Link to full text PDF
File-URL: http://www.palgrave-journals.com/jibs/journal/v46/n8/full/jibs201521a.html
File-Format: text/html
File-Function: Link to full text HTML
Abstract: How do subsidiaries respond to normative demands from both their headquarters and local external constituents? We propose that subsidiaries pay varying levels of attention to demands depending on their peers&rsquo; norm-conforming behavior, resulting in heterogeneous practice implementation. We study the implementation of 25 practices, associated with three corporate social responsibility (CSR) issues in 101 worldwide subsidiaries of a multinational enterprise (MNE). Consistent with the idea that attention is limited and therefore selective, we find that external peers&rsquo; conformity to the CSR norm directs subsidiaries&rsquo; attention toward the CSR-related demands of external constituents at the expense of the demands from the headquarters. However, internal peers&rsquo; conformity increases attention to both external and headquarters&rsquo; demands related to CSR. As higher attention levels result in higher practice implementation, internal and external peers&rsquo; conformity drives the heterogeneity of practice implementation in the MNE. Our results suggest the need to rethink the influence of peers&rsquo; conformity on subsidiaries&rsquo; implementation of practices, as it not only triggers mimicry based on legitimacy but also and simultaneously a more strategic response based on internal and external competitive threats and attention allocation.
Handle: RePEc:pal:jintbs:v:46:y:2015:i:8:p:917-937

